      <div class="card">
        <h2>🌑 Kleshas — Patanjali's 5 yogic afflictions</h2>
        <p>Yoga Sutra II.3-II.9 — the five obstacles the eight limbs were designed to dissolve. <em>Avidya</em> (the root: mistaking the impermanent for the permanent, the body for the self — the master ignorance). And its four branches: <em>asmita</em> (the I-am-ness that confuses the witness with the witnessed), <em>raga</em> (the pull that follows pleasure), <em>dvesha</em> (the push that follows pain), <em>abhinivesha</em> (the cellular clinging to life — present, Patanjali notes, <em>even in the wise</em>). Where the yamas + niyamas are what you <em>practice</em>, the kleshas are what you <em>see</em>. Each page names the source-sutra, what the klesha looks like in love and in work, the gift, the shadow, and the direct ethical antidote.</p>
