      <div class="card">
        <h2>☘️ Celtic Gods — the 12 Tuatha Dé Danann</h2>
        <p>The Iron Age Irish-Celtic pantheon — the People of the Goddess Danu — whose place-names still cover Ireland and whose sabbats are the Wheel of the Year on gab44 (Imbolc is Brigid's day, Lughnasadh is named for Lugh, Samhain is the Morrígan's-and-Macha's threshold, Beltane is Cernunnos-and-Aengus-peak-fertility). Three families. <strong>Sovereigns of the Tuatha</strong> (gold / emerald): <em>the Dagda</em> the all-father with the cauldron-of-plenty and the great-club-of-life-and-death, <em>Danu</em> the primordial river-mother for whom the entire pantheon is named (the Danube and the Don bear her name across the Indo-European arc), <em>Lugh</em> Lámhfada the Many-Skilled sun-king who killed Balor of the Evil Eye with one spear-throw, <em>Nuada</em> Airgetlám the first king with the silver arm whose Lydney-Park Romano-British healing-cult was decoded by J.R.R. Tolkien. <strong>Trí Dée Dána · craft & inspiration</strong> (copper / silver / bronze): <em>Brigid</em> the triple-goddess of fire-poetry-smithcraft and keeper of the perpetual flame at Kildare (Christianized as Saint Brigid without continuity-break, re-lit by the Brigidine Sisters in 1993), <em>Ogma</em> champion-of-words and inventor of the Ogham script (the Gaulish Ogmios whose chains of amber and gold ran from his tongue to the ears of his followers), <em>Goibniu</em> the divine smith who forged the unbeatable spears with three strokes and brewed the Fled Goibnenn ale of immortality, <em>Aengus Óg</em> the dreamer-lover of the Aislinge Óenguso whose four kisses became the songbirds that fly around lovers in Irish poetry forever. <strong>Threshold & Wild</strong> (stag-brown / sea-blue / raven-black / blood-red): <em>Cernunnos</em> the Horned One whose cross-legged Lord-of-the-Beasts pose is preserved on the Pillar of the Boatmen Paris c. 14-37 CE and the Gundestrup Cauldron Denmark c. 100 BCE (the medieval Devil acquired his antlers in 11th-13th-c. Christian art), <em>Manannán mac Lir</em> the sea-god and master of the Féth Fíada magical-mist who hid the Tuatha after their defeat, <em>the Morrígan</em> the triple-Great-Queen of war-and-sovereignty-and-prophecy who united with the Dagda at the ford on Samhain, <em>Macha</em> the sovereignty-and-horses goddess for whom Emain Macha and Ard Macha are named (the foundational Irish proto-feminist Macha-Mongruad who defeated five male claimants to the high-kingship and ruled alone). Each page: Lebor-Gabála / Cath-Maige-Tuired / Táin-Bó-Cúailnge / Mabinogi / Pillar-of-the-Boatmen / Gundestrup-Cauldron source-honest, iconography, invocation, in love + in work, the gift, the shadow (Celtic-Twilight romantic-revival flattening, Iolo-Morganwg 18th-c. forgeries, Margaret-Murray witch-cult-hypothesis, white-nationalist Cernunnos co-option, Christian erasure of the Morrígan, the silent extraction of Brigid into Saint-Brigid, the Saint-Patrick overlay on Ard Macha — named honestly per god), paired zodiac sign + planet + sabbat.</p>
